          "title": "Oracle 1 — The cannibal shepherds (3:1-4)",
          "body": "Micah opens with a summons that drips with irony: 'Hear now, heads of Jacob and rulers of the house of Israel — is it not for you to know justice?' The office of civic ruler existed precisely to administer covenant justice — the protection of the weak from the strong. Micah does not accuse them of ignorance; he accuses them of inversion. They 'know' what justice requires and have chosen its opposite: they 'hate good and love evil' (3:2). The indictment then deploys one of the most viscerally shocking extended metaphors in the prophetic canon. The leaders are described as butchers working through a human body: tearing off skin, stripping flesh from bones, breaking bones, chopping the pieces for the pot. The sequence is clinically precise — skin first, then flesh, then bones, then the pot. Nothing is wasted; the poor are consumed entirely. Douglas Stuart notes that this is not literal cannibalism but a juridical metaphor for economic and judicial exploitation so systematic and so total that every resource of the victim has been extracted. The judgment in verse 4 is the precise inversion of the crime: those who refused to answer the poor will find God refusing to answer them. 'He will hide His face from them at that time.' The hiding of God's face (satar paneh) is the deepest possible expression of covenantal abandonment — the withdrawal of presence, favor, and protection (cf. Psalm 27:9; Isaiah 59:2). The cause is stated plainly: 'because they have practiced evil deeds.' Judgment is not fate; it is consequence."
