          "body": "The third oracle gathers all three leadership groups for a comprehensive indictment. The rulers 'abhor justice and twist everything that is straight' (3:9) — the same inverted relationship to mishpat named in verse 1, now stated even more strongly. 'Abhor' (taav) is the word for active disgust; they do not merely neglect justice but find it repellent. 'Twist what is straight' (aqash yashar) — they bend the very moral order. Verse 10 names their specific crime with geographical precision: building Zion with blood and Jerusalem with iniquity. The holy city is being constructed — literally expanded, fortified, beautified — on the proceeds of judicial murder and exploitation. The blood in the mortar is the blood of the poor. Verse 11 then delivers the chapter's most compact and damning indictment: rulers judge for bribes, priests teach for a fee, prophets divine for money. Every office has been monetized. The sacred functions of judgment, Torah instruction, and divine revelation have been turned into revenue streams. And then — the theological climax of the whole chapter — they justify this corruption with a theological claim: 'Is not the LORD in our midst? Calamity will not come upon us.' This is covenant presumption at its most dangerous. The presence of Yahweh, which the entire Sinai covenant had established as conditional upon obedience (Leviticus 26; Deuteronomy 28), is invoked as an unconditional guarantee. Tim Keller has observed that the most destructive religious corruption is not atheism but the instrumentalization of God — using the true God's name and presence as a shield for personal agenda. That is exactly what verse 11 depicts."
