          "body": "The chapter closes with the most severe single verdict in the entire book: 'Therefore, on account of you Zion will be plowed as a field, Jerusalem will become a heap of ruins, and the mountain of the temple will become high places of a forest.' The triple geographical naming — Zion, Jerusalem, the mountain of the temple — ensures that no reader can miss the target. This is not the destruction of the rural periphery but the elimination of the covenant center. The image of plowing is especially precise: not bombing, burning, or abandoning, but plowing — the act of breaking up and turning over soil, erasing every trace of prior structure. What was built with blood (3:10) will be returned to earth. The temple mount — the highest expression of God's covenant presence among His people — will revert to forested high places, the form of Canaanite worship Israel was supposed to have displaced. The verdict is 'on account of you' (galal) — causal, personal, traceable. Zion does not fall by accident or by the caprice of foreign powers. It falls because identifiable leaders made identifiable choices. The verse is quoted verbatim in Jeremiah 26:18, where it functions as legal precedent in the trial of Jeremiah himself. The court acknowledges that Micah prophesied this and that Hezekiah's repentance forestalled it — confirming that Micah's prophecy, terrifying as it is, was not unconditional fate but covenant warning: repent, and the verdict can be deferred. The destruction of Jerusalem in 586 BC, a century after Micah, was the fulfillment Hezekiah's generation avoided and Zedekiah's generation did not."
