        "excerpt": "Is it not for you to know justice? You who hate good and love evil, who tear off their skin from them and their flesh from their bones.",
        "body": "The opening summons — 'Hear now, heads of Jacob and rulers of the house of Israel' — is a formal covenant lawsuit call, the Hebrew riv (legal dispute) form that the prophets employed when bringing Yahweh's case against His people (cf. Micah 6:1-2; Isaiah 1:2; Hosea 4:1). The lawsuit is directed specifically at the leadership class, and the first accusation is framed as a rhetorical question: 'Is it not for you to know justice?' The question presupposes the answer: yes, of course it is. The heads of Jacob held their office precisely as administrators of covenant law. Deuteronomy 16:18-20 had charged Israel's appointed judges: 'You shall not distort justice; you shall not be partial, and you shall not take a bribe... justice, and only justice, you shall pursue.' Micah's charge is not that the rulers are ignorant of this standard — he assumes they know it. His charge is that knowing it, they have chosen its opposite.\n\nThe butchering metaphor that follows in verses 2-3 is the most sustained piece of visceral imagery in the book. The accumulation of six active verbs — tear off, strip, break, chop, cook — is not emotional excess. It is the precise rhetorical equivalent of what the leaders were doing through the mechanisms of economic exploitation, judicial corruption, and debt-slavery: extracting every resource from the vulnerable until nothing remained. Peter Davids notes in his treatment of the similar imagery in James 5:1-6 that the Old Testament prophets consistently used the language of bodily violence to name systemic economic exploitation, because the moral reality of the latter is as severe as the physical reality of the former.\n\nThe verdict in verse 4 is the lex talionis of divine judgment — the punishment mirrors the crime. The leaders refused to hear the cry of the poor (implied throughout 3:1-3; made explicit in 2:8-9); God will refuse to hear their cry. The hiding of God's face (satar paneh) is the technical covenantal term for the withdrawal of the divine presence — the reversal of the Aaronic blessing of Numbers 6:25 ('the LORD make His face shine on you') and the fulfillment of the covenant curses of Deuteronomy 31:17-18 ('I will hide My face from them'). The phrase 'at that time' marks this as a specific moment of eschatological reckoning, not a general theological principle.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpat* (justice, 3:1) — the right ordering of society according to covenant norms; appearing three times in the chapter (3:1, 8, 9) it functions as the chapter's organizing standard. *Satar paneh* (hide His face, 3:4) — the technical covenantal language of divine abandonment, the reversal of priestly blessing. *Raa maalal* (evil deeds, 3:4) — the plural noun from *maalal* (deed, practice) with *raa* (evil) — not a single act but an established pattern of conduct."
