        "number": 2,
        "title": "The prophets who sold their voice — and the silence that followed",
        "range": "3:5-7",
        "excerpt": "When they have something to bite with their teeth, they cry, 'Peace,' but against him who puts nothing in their mouths they declare holy war.",
        "body": "The second oracle opens with the distinctive prophetic messenger formula — 'Thus says the LORD concerning the prophets' — signaling that what follows is divine speech, not Micah's editorial commentary. The indictment is precise: the false prophets operate a two-tiered pricing model. The client who brings food ('something to bite with their teeth') receives 'Peace' (shalom); the client who brings nothing receives 'holy war' (qadash milchamah — literally 'they sanctify war,' the declaration of a holy conflict). The word shalom here is not merely a greeting. It carries the full covenantal weight of divine well-being, the declaration that things are right between the petitioner and God. The prophets were pronouncing God's favor on the basis of a meal.\n\nThis is the commodification of divine speech. The mechanism of the corruption is not gross immorality but a subtle recalibration of the prophet's primary loyalty — from Yahweh who sends to the patron who pays. Jeremiah faced the same prophetic culture a century later and described it with nearly identical language: they heal the brokenness of God's people superficially, saying *peace, peace* — but there is no peace (Jeremiah 6:14; 8:11). Ezekiel's condemnation in Ezekiel 13:1-16 is even more parallel: false prophets who have seen false visions and lying divination, saying *the LORD declares* — when the LORD has not sent them — and who plastered over Israel's crumbling wall with whitewash. The prophetic consensus is uniform: the prosperity-message calibrated to the audience's desires is the mark of false prophecy.\n\nThe verdict in verses 6-7 is the direct withdrawal of the very gift the false prophets claimed. 'Night without vision' and 'darkness without divination' — the prophetic gift is revoked. The sun going down on the prophets is not merely an inconvenience; in the ancient Near Eastern symbolic world, the sun was the source of royal wisdom, prophetic illumination, and divine communication. Its setting is the cessation of the divine communicative act. And the result is public shame: covering the mouth (atah sapham) was the gesture of a person rendered speechless and disgraced (cf. Leviticus 13:45, where the leper covers his lip — a sign of uncleanness and exclusion).\n\nThe phrase 'there is no answer from God' (ein maaneh me'elohim) in verse 7 is the chapter's most chilling line for the seers. They built an entire livelihood on claiming access to divine communication. The judgment is that the access was never real — and the silence that falls on them reveals it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalom* (peace, 3:5) — covenant well-being, not merely absence of conflict; its procurement by bribe makes it the verbal equivalent of 3:11's judicial corruption. *Qadash milchamah* — 'sanctify war' — to declare a holy war; the religious language applied to a commercial vendetta is the irony of the phrase. *Chozeh* (seer, 3:7) and *qasam* (diviner) — two terms for prophetic practice, the former more associated with legitimate prophecy (cf. Isaiah 1:1; Amos 7:12), the latter with pagan oracular practice (Deuteronomy 18:10). Micah uses both to cover the full range of prophetic office-holders who have forfeited their standing."
