        "title": "Micah's counter-portrait — the Spirit-filled prophet who cannot be bought",
        "range": "3:8",
        "excerpt": "On the other hand I am filled with power — with the Spirit of the LORD — and with justice and courage to make known to Jacob his rebellious act, even to Israel his sin.",
        "body": "Verse 8 stands as the structural and theological fulcrum of the entire chapter. Its opening adversative — 'but as for me' (ulam anoki) — is one of the sharpest contrasting hinges in the Hebrew prophetic literature. Coming immediately after the description of silenced, shamed false prophets, it announces a different kind of prophetic existence. The contrast is not primarily about outcome (Micah succeeds where they fail) but about source and content.\n\nThree endowments fill Micah: power (koach), the Spirit of the LORD (ruach Yahweh), and justice and courage (mishpat ugevurah). The syntax is slightly ambiguous — 'the Spirit of the LORD' may modify 'power,' so that the whole phrase reads 'filled with power, namely the Spirit of the LORD, and also justice and courage.' Either way, the ruach is the source from which the others flow. The Spirit is not one item in a list; He is the supply who makes the others possible. The Old Testament theology of prophetic inspiration is consistently pneumatological: Moses (Numbers 11:17), the seventy elders (Numbers 11:25), Elijah (2 Kings 2:15), Ezekiel (Ezekiel 2:2), and — in the New Covenant fulfillment — all believers (Joel 2:28-29, quoted by Peter in Acts 2:17).\n\nThe content of Micah's Spirit-filled message is 'to make known to Jacob his rebellious act, even to Israel his sin.' The two terms — pesha (willful transgression, rebellion against covenant authority) and chattaah (sin, moral failure) — are a comprehensive pair covering both the deliberate and the habitual dimensions of Israel's guilt. Micah's Spirit-empowered ministry is defined precisely by what the false prophets refused to say: the specific, named, unvarnished sin of the leadership class. Chuck Swindoll, commenting on authentic pastoral ministry, observed that the willingness to name sin publicly and specifically — rather than speaking in comfortable generalities — is among the most costly and necessary marks of genuine prophetic courage. Micah models it here at personal risk: the same leadership class he is accusing controls the social and economic structures within which he lives.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ulam* (but as for me, 3:8) — a strong adversative, rare but emphatic; used in Job 1:11; 2:5 and here to mark an absolute contrast. *Ruach Yahweh* (Spirit of the LORD) — the animating breath-power of Yahweh that in the OT endows prophets for speech (Numbers 24:2; 1 Samuel 19:20; 2 Chronicles 15:1). *Pesha* (transgression, rebellion) — active revolt against a sovereign; *chattaah* (sin) — the missing of the mark. The pairing is a merism covering the full range of moral failure."
